    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Visit to North Korea</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from John H Kim (National Association of Korean Americans) on Oct 25 editorial holds Pres Clinton should visit North Korea even if visit results in no major accords</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Even if concrete results cannot be assured in visiting North Korea (''In the Land of Kim Jong Il,'' editorial, Oct. 25), it is still worthwhile for President Clinton to visit there. The prospect of achieving some success in his foreign policy initiatives is much brighter in Korea than in many other hot spots around the world.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Even if concrete results cannot be assured in visiting North Korea (''In the Land of Kim Jong Il,'' editorial, Oct. 25), it is still worthwhile for President Clinton to visit there. The prospect of achieving some success in his foreign policy initiatives is much brighter in Korea than in many other hot spots around the world.</p>
        <p>His visit would help in reducing tensions in the Far East and ending the Korean War in particular. It is about time that we formally ended this tragic, costly war and let Koreans realize a peaceful reunion of their proud nation.</p>
        <p>Even if his visit resulted in no major agreements, Mr. Clinton could pave the way for the next president to conclude a permanent peace settlement in Korea.</p>
        <p>JOHN H. KIM  New York, Oct. 25, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is president of the New York chapter, National Association of Korean Americans.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
